Font Properties: Changing The Appearance Of Text

- FONT SIZE
i.e.
<h1>
    font-size: 20px
</h1>
-> 1px (1 pixel) = 1/96th inch ~ 0.26mm
-> 1pt (1 point) = 1/72nd inch ~ 0.35 mm - used in word documents
-> 1em (1 "em" - pronounced like the letter 'm') = 100% of parent; full width of the letter 'm'
BUT useful metric because it's relative size. 
i.e. if
<body> has a font size of 20px
    <h1>Some random content</h1> has a font size of 1em,
</body>
then that means the size of h1=size of body; h1 = 20 px also. If it was 2em then it'd = 40 px etc
-> 1rem = RECOMMENDED OVER USING 'em' because it's not embedded in other elements so easier to 
configure. Similar to 1 em, 100% of root of html file (normally an html element that encloses
everything inside). 

- FONT WEIGHT
i.e.
<h1>
    font-weight: normal
</h1>
-> keywords i.e. 'normal' or 'bold'
-> relative to parent i.e. 'lighter' or 'bolder' (+/- 100)
-> number between 100-900 (100 = lighter, 900 = bolder)

- FONT FAMILY
-> Basically the name of the font, although tends to be multiple in case some typefaces are 
unavailable (e.g. Helvetica can't be found on windows). 
-> Typefaces with mutiple words in their name need a quotation mark e.g. "Times New Roman"
-> Backup type font needs to be the same type as the first font (e.g. serif, serif)
i.e.
<h1>
    font-family: Helvetica, sans-serif
</h1>

Serif vs. Sans-Serif:
Sans-Serif: If the edges of the letters are at right angles e.g. Helvetica
Serif: Anything else such as the edges being rounded/ curved e.g. Times New Roman

- TEXT Align
h1 {
    text-align: center/left/right/start/end
}